'''''Everything Tastes Better with Bacon: 70&nbsp;Fabulous Recipes for Every Meal of the Day''''' is a book about cooking with [[bacon]] written by Sara Perry. She is an author, food commentator and columnist for ''[[The Oregonian]]''. The book was published in the United States in 2002 by [[Chronicle Books]], and in a [[French language]] edition in 2004 by Les Editions de l'Homme in [[Montreal]]. In it, Perry describes her original concept of recipes combining sugar and bacon. Her book includes recipes for bacon-flavored dishes and desserts.

The book received positive reviews and its recipes were selected for inclusion in ''The Best American Recipes 2003<U+2013>2004''. The ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'' classed it as among one of the "most interesting and unique cookbooks" published, the ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' highlighted it in the article "Favorite Cookbooks for 2002" and ''[[The Denver Post]]'' included it in a list of best cookbooks of 2002. Recipes from the work have been featured in related cookbooks.

==Background==
[[File:Sara (mexico).jpeg|thumb|Sara Perry in 2009|alt=Woman wearing glasses and white shirt, with head rested on hand]]
Sara Perry is a resident of [[Portland, Oregon]] and a columnist for ''The Oregonian'',{{sfn|Julian|2002|p=33}}{{sfn|Browning-Blas|2002|p=M7}} a radio restaurant commentator{{sfn|Perry|2003|p=121}} and a cookbook author. Before ''Everything Tastes Better with Bacon'' she wrote four books: ''The New Complete Coffee Book'', ''The New Tea Book'', ''Christmastime Treats'' and ''Weekends with the Kids''.{{sfn|Perry|2003|p=121}} Her editor at [[Chronicle Books]] suggested bacon as a cookbook subject.{{sfn|Keeler|2002|p=1C}} Bacon's popularity and usage was increasing, but Perry believed that a paucity of recipes would make writing the book difficult.{{sfn|Keeler|2002|p=1C}} Recalling her fondness for honey-baked [[ham]], she combined sugar and bacon to create dishes.{{sfn|Keeler|2002|p=1C}} Perry realized that bacon could be used to add seasoning in flavoring dishes, including salads and pastas.{{sfn|The Sacramento Bee staff|2002|p=F1}} She observed that bacon increased the sweet and [[salt]]y tastes of food.{{sfn|Smith|2002|p=D1}} ''Everything Tastes Better with Bacon'' was published in English in [[paperback|paperback format]] by Chronicle Books in 2002.{{sfn|WorldCat|2011a}}{{sfn|Perry|2002|p=4}} The book sold for a retail price of {{Currency|18.95}} in its initial publication.{{sfn|Fabricant|2002}}{{sfn|Paulson|2003|p=16}} A French paperback edition was published in 2004 by Les Editions de l'Homme, as part of its "Tout un plat!" ("What a dish!") series.{{sfn|WorldCat|2011b}}{{sfn|Perry|2004}}

==Content summary==
Perry explains her feelings about bacon in the book's introduction, observing that its smell while cooking helps start her day and provide her with a sense of calmness.{{sfn|Crooks|2002|p=D1}} The beginning of the book provides background on the phrase "[[wikt:bring home the bacon|bringing home the bacon]]", introduces the reader to types of bacon and describes storage methods.{{sfn|Saunders|2002|p=C4}} The book offers 70&nbsp;recipes for bacon-flavored dishes,{{sfn|English|2002}}{{sfn|McCarthy|2002|p=A1}} in 9 chapters organized by topic, including breakfast, leaf vegetables, pasta meals, side dishes, party servings, [[dessert]]s and [[appetizer]]s.{{sfn|Perry|2002|p=7}}{{sfn|Zeldes|2006|p=S1}}{{sfn|Lawson|2003|p=12D}} Recipes include a bacon sandwich using other ingredients,{{sfn|Meitus|2003b|p=3D}} a bacon crunch topping for [[ice cream]],{{sfn|Longino|2002}} a bacon concoction to top a fruit crisp,{{sfn|McCarthy|2002|p=A1}} and a [[pie crust]] that incorporates bacon.{{sfn|Eddy|2002a|p=K5}} Methods are offered for cooking bacon on a [[stovetop]], in an oven and under a griller to maximize its flavor and appearance.{{sfn|Lawson|2003|p=12D}}{{sfn|Mahoney|2003|p=D1}}{{sfn|Cichy|2003|p=4E}} The book is illustrated with photographs by Sheri Giblin.{{sfn|Hoedel|2002|p=E2}}

==Reception==
''Everything Tastes Better with Bacon'' was positively received by reviewers and food critics. The ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' reported that it sold 30,000 copies in its first month.{{sfn|Eddy|2002b|p=1}} Janet F. Keeler of the ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'' commented positively on the book's title.{{sfn|Keeler|2003|p=1D}} She noted the work was covered by food critics, who included its recipes in articles about the subject.{{sfn|Keeler|2003|p=1D}} Keeler interviewed Fran McCullough, author of ''The Best American Recipes 2003<U+2013>2004'', who posited that the [[Atkins diet]] had helped increase the popularity of bacon usage.{{sfn|Keeler|2003|p=1D}}{{efn|The [[Atkins diet]] was developed by physician [[Robert Atkins (nutritionist)|Robert Atkins]] and emphasized higher meat consumption as part of a low [[carbohydrate]] plan.{{sfn|Aldana|2005|p=215}}}} She classed it among the "most interesting and unique cookbooks" published.{{sfn|Keeler|2008|p=5E}} Giblin's photography received favorable commentary from Cindy Hoedel of ''[[The Kansas City Star]]''.{{sfn|Hoedel|2002|p=E2}} Literary critic [[Dwight Garner (critic)|Dwight Garner]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' included the book in a list of favorites among recent cooking publications.{{sfn|Garner|2002|p=54}} The review was critical of the author's dessert recipes, but agreed with her overall argument for increased use of bacon in cooking.{{sfn|Garner|2002|p=54}}

''[[The Arizona Daily Star]]'' highlighted the book in their "Hot Reads" section.{{sfn|Burch|2002|p=F1}} Assistant Texas Taste Editor for ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' Laura H. Ehret wrote that the book successfully conveys the experience of consuming bacon.{{sfn|Ehret|2002|p=6F}} Marty Meitus wrote for the ''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'' that the book had increased his appetite for bacon dishes.{{sfn|Meitus|2003a|p=5D}} Meitus recommended dessert recipes, including [[Hazelnut]]-Bacon [[Candy]] Crunch, [[Peanut Butter]] Cookies with Bacon Brittle, [[Pear]]-[[Apple Crisp]] with Brown Sugar-Bacon Topping and Ruby [[Raisin]] [[Mincemeat]] [[Tart]].{{sfn|Meitus|2003a|p=5D}} Steve Smith, executive chef at Dixon's Downtown Grill in [[Denver]], was inspired by Perry's "Maple Sundae" recipe and used it to create his own [[macadamia]]-bacon crunch ice cream dessert.{{sfn|Browning-Blas|2003|p=F01}}

Writing for the ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'', Marlene Parrish gave the book a favorable review, highlighting it in her article "Favorite Cookbooks for 2002".{{sfn|Parrish|2002|p=F1}} She wrote that she enjoyed sampling the recipes from the book.{{sfn|Parrish|2002|p=F1}} Parrish added that [[Robert Atkins (nutritionist)|Robert Atkins]], creator of the Atkins diet, would think favorably of the "[[Gorgonzola]] [[Cheeseburger]]s with Bacon" dish.{{sfn|Parrish|2002|p=F1}} ''[[The Denver Post]]'' included the book in a list of best cookbooks of 2002.{{sfn|Husted|2002|p=FF9}} Another article for the same newspaper highlighted recipes in the book, including [[Spaghetti alla Carbonara]] and [[Cobb Salad]], Pear-Apple Crisp with Brown Sugar-Bacon Topping and Bacon Brittle.{{sfn|Browning-Blas|2002|p=M-07}} A review in ''[[The Toronto Star]]'' criticized Perry's lack of creativity in her choice of recipes.{{sfn|The Toronto Star staff|2002|p=D05}} The review concluded the book was a good deal compared to other cookbooks on the subject, while noting its lack of comprehensiveness with the small number of total recipes included.{{sfn|The Toronto Star staff|2002|p=D05}} Michele Anna Jordan of ''[[The Press Democrat]]'' recommended Perry's work, and commented that the author's zest for the subject was contagious.{{sfn|Jordan|2002|p=D1}}

==Impact==
According to the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' and the ''St. Petersburg Times'', ''Everything Tastes Better with Bacon'' is a niche work in the cookbook genre.{{sfn|Zeldes|2006|p=S1}}{{sfn|Keeler|2008|p=5E}} Perry stated that bacon had undergone a [[renaissance]] period.{{sfn|Paulson|2003|p=16}} ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'' noted in a 2003 article that bacon was becoming an increasingly used cooking ingredient, despite having been maligned by nutritionists.{{sfn|Paulson|2003|p=16}} Recipes from the book were selected for inclusion in ''The Best American Recipes 2003<U+2013>2004: The Year's Top Picks from Books, Magazines, Newspapers and the Internet''.{{sfn|McCullough|2003|pp=84<U+2013>85, 280, 284}}{{sfn|Bonwich|2004|p=1}} Perry's recipe for "Succulent Bacon-Wrapped Shrimp" was referenced in the 2003 book ''Smoke & Spice: Cooking with Smoke, the Real Way to Barbecue''.{{sfn|Jamison|2003|p=340}} Fran McCullough, the author of ''The Best American Recipes'', commented that the book was a surprising addition to the field.{{sfn|Keeler|2003|p=1D}} ''[[The Atlantic]]'' said that three years after the book's publication, bacon had become as popular as chocolate or olive oil.{{sfn|Kummer|2005}} Leah A. Zeldes observed in a 2006 article for the ''Chicago Sun-Times'' that the book contributed to the body of works that display the adaptability of bacon in recipes.{{sfn|Zeldes|2006|p=S1}} In his 2009 book ''Hungry Monkey'', author Matthew Amster-Burton commented on the phenomena involving bacon and books on the subject in prior years, listing the book along with ''[[The Bacon Cookbook]]'' and ''[[Seduced by Bacon]]''.{{sfn|Amster-Burton|2009|p=63}} A 2013 article in the [[England|British]] newspaper ''[[The Independent]]'' cited the book as an example of increasing interest in pork.{{sfn|Muston|2013|pp=44<U+2013>45}}

